The dataset (344 rows, 4 columns: assembly, revenue_item, year, contribution_to_total_revenue), cover 6 assemblies (WA, Tamale, Bolgatanga, Yendi, East Mamprusi, West Gonja), 8 revenue items (Property Rates, Other Rates, Fees, Fines, Licences, Land (incl Miscellaneous), Rent, Investment), and years 20172024.

The contribution_to_total_revenue is right-skewed (skewness = 1.21, kurtosis = 4.27), with a mean of 12.6%, median of 8.2%, and max of 71.9%. The 1st quartile (0.4%) and min (0%) indicate many low-value contributions, while the 3rd quartile (20.3%) and max suggest a few high-impact cases. The histogram below confirms a long right tail.

Most revenue items contribute modestly (~020%), but rare cases ( 71.9%) dominate in specific assemblies or years The median (8.2%) is a more reliable measure than the mean due to skewness.

Assemblies: Bolgatanga has slightly more observations (64, 18.6%), while others (WA, Tamale, Yendi, East Mamprusi, West Gonja) have 56 each (16.3%).

Revenue Items: Each item (Fees, Fines, etc.) has 43 observations (12.5%)

Years: 2017 has only 8 observations (2.3%), while 20182024 each have 48 (14.0%)

Low Median Contributions with High Variability: The median contribution (8.2%) is below the mean (12.6%). The standard deviation (13.73%) indicates some variability, with contributions ranging from 0% to 71.9%. The 3rd quartile (20.3%) shows that 25% of cases contribute significantly.

Assembly Contributions:

Means: West Gonja leads (13.50%), followed by Bolgatanga (13.13%), WA (12.50%), East Mamprusi (12.48%), Tamale (12.25%), and Yendi (11.79%). Means are close, suggesting similar average contributions.

Medians: Bolgatanga has the highest median (12.70%), followed by Tamale (9.95%), Yendi (8.22%), East Mamprusi (6.35%), WA (6.00%), and West Gonja (5.80%). Lower medians indicate skewness within assemblies.

Variability: West Gonja has the highest SD (18.22%) and max (71.9%), while Bolgatanga and Yendi are less variable (SDs ~11.9%). Max contributions range from 38.6% (Yendi) to 71.9% (West Gonja).

Dominance: Licences dominate in most assemblies ( WA, Tamale, Bolgatanga), except West Gonja (Fees) and Yendi (Rent). Dominance ratios are low (0.060.11), indicating diversified contributions.

Bolgatangas high median and low SD suggest consistent contributions, while West Gonjas high variability aligns with the revenue growths volatility ( Tamales SD = 10,602.30%). Tamales moderate performance contrasts with its rev_growth leadership (mean = 2047.67%).

Revenue Item Contributions: Licences and Fees Dominate: Leaders: Licences (mean = 35.64%, median = 35.00%, max = 68.3%) and Fees (mean = 23.27%, median = 21.90%, max = 71.9%) have the highest contributions, with 100% presence (non-zero contributions) and peaks in 2023 (Licences) and 2024 (Fees).

Moderate Contributors: Property Rates (mean = 12.43%, median = 9.95%, max = 32.9%), Rent (mean = 10.96%, median = 11.10%, max = 38.6%), and Land (mean = 9.96%, median = 8.80%, max = 33.3%) show moderate contributions, with Property Rates peaking in 2022 and Land in 2018.

Low Contributors: Other Rates (mean = 2.75%, median = 1.70%, max = 15.0%), Fines (mean = 2.31%, median = 0.30%, max = 20.2%), and Investment (mean = 1.66%, median = 0.00%, max = 18.5%) have low contributions, with Fines and Investment often at 0% (presence = 55.8364.29%).

Licences and Fees are reliable pillars, mirroring their stability in rev_growth (medians 14.35%, 13.90%). Low contributions from Fines and Investment align with rev_growths volatility (e.g., Fines max = 43,990%) and stagnation (Investment median = 0%).

Temporal Trends: Stable Means, Declining Medians: Means: Yearly means are stable (~11.513.7%), with a slight peak in 2021 (13.65%) and 2020 (13.07%). 2017s mean (12.50%) is based on only 8 observations, limiting reliability.

Medians: Medians decline over time, from 11.65% (2017) and 11.10% (2019) to 5.45% (2023) and 3.80% (2024), despite high max values (68.3% in 2023, 71.9% in 2024).

Variability: SDs increase from 11.10% (2017) to 16.43% (2024), with max contributions rising from 25.9% (2017) to 71.9% (2024). Gini coefficients rise from 0.51 (2019) to 0.65 (20232024), indicating growing inequality in contributions.

Entropy: Shannon entropy peaks in 2019 (3.32) and declines to 3.09 (2024), suggesting reduced diversity in contributions over time.

Stable means mask a shift toward lower medians and higher outliers, aligning with rev_growths 2023 peak (mean = 1479.85%) and 2024 decline (median = 0%). The 20232024 high Gini reflects concentration in Fees/Licences.

Observation: High 2023 contributions ( Licences at 68.3%) align with rev_growths growth spikes (Property Rates at 2418.6%), suggesting shared drivers ( policy reforms).

Conclusions

Dominance of Licences and Fees:

Finding: Licences (mean = 35.64%, median = 35.00%, max = 68.3%, 2023 peak) and Fees (mean = 23.27%, median = 21.90%, max = 71.9%, 2024 peak) are the primary contributors to total revenue, with 100% non-zero presence and significant differences from other items (Kruskal-Wallis p < 0.001). Visualizations (bar plots, alluvial plots) confirm their consistent high shares, especially post-2020.

Comparison with rev_growth: Mirrors their reliability (medians 14.35%, 13.90%), emphasizing stability across both contribution and growth metrics.

Conclusion: Licences and Fees are the backbone of revenue stability, making them critical for sustained fiscal planning.

Declining Median Contributions and Rising Inequality:

Finding: Median contributions drop from 12.05% (2021) to 3.80% (2024), despite stable means (~11.513.7%). Gini coefficients rise from 0.51 (2019) to 0.65 (20232024), and Shannon entropy falls from 3.32 (2019) to 3.09 (2024), indicating growing concentration in Licences/Fees. Line plots and box plots show outliers (max = 71.9% in 2024).

Comparison with rev_growth: Aligns with 2024s decline (median = 0%, mean = -1.84%) and 2023s peak (mean = 1479.85%), suggesting a shift toward fewer high-impact items.

Conclusion: Declining medians and increasing inequality signal reliance on key items, necessitating diversification strategies to mitigate risks.

Assembly Performance: Regional Disparities Despite Statistical Similarity: Finding: Bolgatanga leads in median contribution (12.70%), followed by Tamale (9.95%), while West Gonja (5.80%) is volatile (max = 71.9%, SD = 18.22%). No significant differences across assemblies (Kruskal-Wallis p = 0.923), likely due to skewness (1.21). Heatmaps and box plots suggest higher contributions in Tamale/WA (20232024) and lower in Bolgatanga/East Mamprusi.

Comparison with rev_growth: Bolgatangas consistency contrasts with its growth stagnation (median = 0%), while Tamales moderate contributions underperform its growth leadership (mean = 2047.67%).

Conclusion: Regional disparities exist practically (e.g., Tamale vs.Bolgatanga), despite statistical non-significance, highlighting the need for targeted interventions in underperforming assemblies.

Underperformance of Fines, Investment, and Other Rates:

Finding: Fines (mean = 2.31%, median = 0.30%), Investment (mean = 1.66%, median = 0.00%), and Other Rates (mean = 2.75%, median = 1.70%) contribute minimally, with frequent zero values (presence = 55.8364.29%). Box plots show tight ranges, and alluvial plots likely depict their declining shares.

Comparison with rev_growth: Reflects Fines volatility (max = 43,990%) and Investments stagnation (median = 0%), indicating structural weaknesses.

Conclusion: These items are unreliable revenue sources, requiring policy reforms to enhance their contribution or reallocation of efforts to stronger items.

Temporal Peaks in 20232024 with Volatility:

Finding: High contributions in 2023 (Licences at 68.3%) and 2024 (Fees at 71.9%) align with increasing variability (SD = 16.43% in 2024). Heatmaps and line plots highlight these peaks, with 2017s sparse data (N = 8, 2.3%) limiting early insights.

Comparison with rev_growth: Matches 2023s growth spike ( Property Rates at 2418.6%) and 2024s decline, suggesting shared economic or policy drivers (tax reforms).

Conclusion: The 20232024 peaks offer lessons for boosting contributions, but volatility underscores the need for stable revenue streams.

Policy and Strategic Implications Strengthen Licences and Fees: Enhance collection and enforcement mechanisms for Licences and Fees, given their dominant and stable contributions (medians 35%, 21.9%), to ensure reliable 2025 revenue.

Replicate 20232024 Successes: Investigate drivers of high contributions ( Fees at 71.9% in West Gonja, Licences at 68.3% in 2023) to replicate across assemblies, leveraging insights from rev_growths 2023 peaks.

Address Regional Disparities: Implement targeted interventions in Bolgatanga and East Mamprusi (low medians 6.3512.70%) to boost Licences/Fees contributions, addressing their consistent underperformance in both datasets.

Improve Weak Items: Reform Fines, Investment, and Other Rates (medians 01.70%) through policy changes ( better enforcement, investment incentives) or redirect efforts to stronger items, given their parallels in rev_growth.

Mitigate 2024 Decline: Prepare contingency budgets for 2025, anticipating continued low median contributions (3.80% in 2024), consistent with rev_growths decline (mean = -1.84%).

The contribution_to_rev analysis reveals a revenue landscape dominated by Licences and Fees, with significant contributions in 20232024 but declining medians and rising inequality by 2024. While assemblies show practical disparities ( Bolgatangas consistency, West Gonjas volatility), statistical differences are limited to revenue items, driven by Licences/Fees dominance. Parallels with rev_growth underscore shared trends (2023 peaks, 2024 declines, regional gaps). For 2025, the assemblies should prioritize Licences/Fees, replicate 20232024 successes, and address underperforming items and regions to ensure fiscal stability.
